SIMPLE: lineman
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lineman
<hw>Line"man</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧n"m⟦acr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Linemen</plw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧n"m⟦ecr⟧n)</pr>.</plu>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who carries the line in surveying, etc.; the
surveyor who marks positions with a range pole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A man employed to examine the rails of a railroad to
see if they are in good condition; also, a man employed to install or
repair telegraph, telephone, television cable, or power lines. Also
called <altname>linesman</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Football)</fld> <def>A player whose position is in
the first (forward) line, as opposed to a <contr>back</contr>; one who
plays on the line of scrimmage.</def> <specif>specifically:</specif>
<def>a center, guard, or tackle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A ladies' man who is especially adept at inventing
effective introductory phrases (<ecol><b>pick-up lines</b></ecol>) to
gain a woman's attention.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>the position of a player on a football team who is
stationed on the line of scrimmage.</def> <wns>[wns=4]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>linemen</ent>⟦br⟧
